{
  "texts": [
    "43 Design defects refer to foreseeable risks of harm associated with the product that could have been minimised or averted by adopting a reasonable alternative design.",
    "Information defects are foreseeable risks that could have been achieved by providing adequate instructions or warnings.",
    "44 U.S. courts predominantly use the risk-utility test for design and information defects.",
    "45 According to this test, a product is considered defective if it could have reduced or avoided foreseeable risks of harm by adopting a reasonable alternative design.",
    "46 This essentially applies a negligence framework (Masterman & Viscusi, 2020, 185)."
  ]
}